1359":"1340–1359","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1342–1359":"1342–1359","1344–1359":"1344–1359","1346–1359":"1346–1359","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1340":"1340","abt 1340":"about 1340","1382":"1382","abt 1342":"about 1342","abt 1344":"about 1344","abt 1346":"about 1346","1359":"1359","1304":"1304","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","about 1339":"about 1339","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","about 1310":"about 1310","of Surrey, Engl":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Molesey, Surrey, England":"Molesey, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Surrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the county of Surrey, from Old English <i>sūther</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>gē</i> ‘district, region’, possibly a reference to its position south of the Thames."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Surrey was born about 1310, in Surrey, England, United Kingdom. She married Samson de Matham about 1339, in England. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1304–1358":"1304–1358","1340–1359":"1340–1359","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1342–1359":"1342–1359","1344–1359":"1344–1359","1346–1359":"1346–1359","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1340":"1340","abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1382":"1382","abt 1342":"umbes 1342","abt 1344":"umbes 1344","abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1359":"1359","1304":"1304","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","about 1310":"umbes 1310","of Surrey, Engl":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Molesey, Surrey, England":"Molesey, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1304–1358":"1304–1358","1340–1359":"1340–1359","1340–1382":"1340